  have h_le : ‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ.essSup (spectrum ‚Ąā a) ‚Č§ C := by
    apply ‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ.essSup_le
    intro x hx
    have hfx : ‚ÄĖf x‚ÄĖ ‚Č§ C := hf_bounded x
    simpa using hfx
```

For the reverse inequality, we need to show that `C ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ.essSup (spectrum ‚Ąā a)`. By definition of `essSup`, we need to show that for any `őĶ > 0`, there is a set `S` of measure `‚Č• 0` such that `‚ÄĖf x‚ÄĖ ‚Č• C - őĶ` for all `x ‚ąą S`. But since `‚ÄĖf x‚ÄĖ ‚Č§ C` everywhere, we can take `S = ‚ąÖ`, which has measure `0`. Then `‚ÄĖf x‚ÄĖ ‚Č• C - őĶ` is trivially true for all `x ‚ąą ‚ąÖ`.

```tactics
have h_ge : C ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ.essSup (spectrum ‚Ąā a) := by
  have h1 : ‚ąÄ x, ‚ÄĖf x‚ÄĖ ‚Č§ C := by
    intro x
    apply hf_bounded x
```

To show `C ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ.essSup (spectrum ‚Ąā a)`, we use the fact that `‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ.essSup (spectrum ‚Ąā a)` is the infimum of the set of upper bounds for `‚ÄĖf x‚ÄĖ`. Since `C` is an upper bound (as shown by `h1`), `C` must be greater than or equal to the infimum.

```tactics
have h2 : ‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ.essSup (spectrum ‚Ąā a) ‚Č• C := by
  have h3 : ‚ąÄ x, ‚ÄĖf x‚ÄĖ ‚Č§ C := h1
```

We need to show that `C ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ.essSup (spectrum ‚Ąā a)`. By definition, `‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ.essSup (spectrum ‚Ąā a) = inf { M : ‚ĄĚ | ‚ąÄ x, ‚ÄĖf x‚ÄĖ ‚Č§ M }`. Since `C` is in this set (as shown by `h3`), `C ‚Č• ‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ.essSup (spectrum ‚Ąā a)` is false. We need `C ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ.essSup (spectrum ‚Ąā a)`.

Let's correct this. To show `C ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ.essSup (spectrum ‚Ąā a)`, we need to show that `C` is a lower bound for the set of upper bounds. But `‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ.essSup (spectrum ‚Ąā a)` is the infimum of the set of upper bounds. So we need to show that `C ‚Č• ‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ.essSup (spectrum ‚Ąā a)`. This is not what we want.

We want to show `‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ.essSup (spectrum ‚Ąā a) ‚Č§ C`. This is what `h_le` shows. The equality `‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ.essSup (spectrum ‚Ąā a) = C` follows from `h_le` and the fact that `C` is the least upper bound.

```tactics
